{
  "text": "+ memory T-cells and/or IL-10 produced by B-cell and monocytes should be explored [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Some reviews about this theme suggest that despite the difficulty to monitor cellular immunity biomarkers, due to their low frequency and broad antigen specificity, the tracking of theses target biomarkers by phenotypic analysis of T. cruzispecific immune response can represent a promising tool for posttherapeutic evaluation in Chagas diseases hosts. There is a general consensus that, regardless of the fact that parasitological cure cannot be achieved in some cases, the ability of the etiological treatment to shift the immune response towards a mixed and balanced profile, with a IL-10-modulated and IFN--driven-proinflammatory microenvironment, is a benefit to be considered even in not cured patients. Several immunological mediators have also been explored with this purpose [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
